<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><refentry version="5.0-subset Scilab" xml:id="imbwperim" xml:lang="en" xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><refnamediv><refname>imbwperim</refname><refpurpose>Return a binary boundary mask.</refpurpose></refnamediv><refsynopsisdiv><title>Syntax</title><synopsis>perimeter = imbwperim(image); perimeter = imbwperim(image, connectivity)</synopsis></refsynopsisdiv><refsection><title>Parameters</title><variablelist><varlistentry><term>image</term><listitem><para>Binary or numeric 2D image.</para></listitem></varlistentry><varlistentry><term>connectivity</term><listitem><para>4 or 8. The default is 8.</para></listitem></varlistentry><varlistentry><term>perimeter</term><listitem><para>Boolean boundary mask.</para></listitem></varlistentry></variablelist></refsection><refsection><title>Description</title><para><function>imbwperim</function> is a MATLAB-style compatibility entry point for <function>bwborder</function> and returns boundary pixels rather than a scalar perimeter.</para></refsection><refsection><title>Examples</title><programlisting><![CDATA[mask = zeros(7, 7) == 1; mask(2:6, 2:6) = %t; imedge = imbwperim(mask); imshow(imedge);]]></programlisting></refsection><refsection role="see also"><title>See also</title><simplelist type="inline"><member><link linkend="bwborder">bwborder</link></member><member><link linkend="imperimeter">imperimeter</link></member></simplelist></refsection><refsection><title>Authors</title><simplelist type="vert"><member>Tan Chin Luh</member></simplelist></refsection><refsection><title>History</title><informaltable border="1"><tr><td>Version</td><td>Description</td></tr><tr><td>5.0.0</td><td>Compatibility entry point introduced in development Step 3.</td></tr></informaltable></refsection></refentry>
